      "content": "The legal community is deeply divided on this, with the \"living document\" approach being the dominant view of the modern Supreme Court but heavily criticized by originalists who believe the Constitution should be interpreted strictly according to the Framers' original intent. While many scholars and justices argue that adapting the law to new societal realities is necessary for justice, opponents contend that this judicial activism allows judges to impose their own policy preferences rather than faithfully applying the text. Ultimately, the legitimacy of substantive due process depends entirely on whether you view the Constitution as a fixed set of rules or a flexible framework for protecting evolving human rights.",
